mcp-server
publishing-for-agents
platforms
```

## How the lessons fit together

| Position | Lesson | The deliverable (CLI) |
|----------|--------|------------------------|
| Set the stage | Introduction | — |
| Set the stage | Elements of Style — Rules | — |
| Foundation | Command line + Git Bash | `eos-command-line` |
| Foundation | Version control | `eos-version-control` |
| Foundation | Conda environments | `eos-env-diff` |
| Foundation | Interactive computing | `eos-kernel-check` |
| Build | Reusable CLIs | `eos-hello` (teaching exemplar) |
| Build | Containers | `eos-container-check` |
| Build | Nextflow | `eos-nextflow-step` |
| Build | Nextflow modules | `eos-modules` |
| Scale | Federated computing | `eos-federated-compute` |
| Scale | Federated learning | `eos-federated-learn` |
| Agent | MCP server | `eos-mcp-nsforest` (the headline) |
| Agent | Publishing for agents | `eos-publish` |
| Run | Platforms | `eos-platforms` |

Every CLI in that right-hand column installs as a console script via
the repo's `pyproject.toml`. That means every deliverable here is, on
day one, callable by an AI agent through an [MCP server](mcp-server.md).

## What "complete" looks like at each lesson

You're done with a lesson when you can answer **yes** to all three:

1. **I can run the example end-to-end on my own machine.**
2. **I can explain to a teammate why we're doing it this way.**
3. **My future self (six months from now) could rerun it from the artifacts alone.**

That third one is the secret. Workflows are letters to your future self.
